cted Papers of the 1965 North American Fur Trade Conference.'' St. Paul: Minnesota Historical Society, 1967.\n* Bolus, Malvina. ''People and Pelts: Selected Papers.'' Winnipeg: Peguis Publishers, 1972.\n* Judd, Carol M. and Arthur J. Ray, eds. ''Old Trails and New Directions: Papers of the Third North American Fur Trade Conference.'' Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1980.\n* Buckley, Thomas C., ed. ''Rendezvous: Selected Papers of the Fourth North American Fur Trade Conference, 1981.'' St. Paul, Minnesota: The Conference, 1984.\n* Trigger, Bruce G., Morantz, Toby Elaine, and Louise Dech\u00eane. ''Le Castor Fait Tout: Selected Papers of the Fifth North American Fur Trade Conference, 1985.'' Montreal: The Society, 1987.\n* Brown, Jennifer S. H., [[William J. Eccles|Eccles, W. J.]], and Donald P. Heldman. ''The Fur Trade Revisited: Selected Papers of the Sixth North American Fur Trade Conference, Mackinac Island, Michigan, 1991.'' East Lansing: Michigan State University Press, 1994.\n* Fiske, Jo-Anne, Sleeper-Smith, Susan, and William Wicken, eds. ''New Faces of the Fur Trade: Selected Papers of the Seventh North American Fur Trade Conference, Halifax, Nova Scotia, 1995''. East Lansing: Michigan State University Press, 1998.\n* Johnston, Louise, ed. ''Aboriginal People and the Fur Trade: Proceedings of the 8th North American Fur Trade Conference, Akwesasne''. Cornwall, Ontario: Akwesasne Notes Pub., 2001.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fur trade}}\n{{Commons category|Fur traders}}\n{{Americana Poster|Fur Trade, The|the fur trade}}\n* [http://www.civilization.ca/cmc/exhibitions/hist/canoe/can00eng.shtml The Canadian Museum of Civilization \u2013 Great Fur Trade Canoes]\n*[http://digitalcollections.library.ubc.ca/cdm/landingpage/collection/bullock H. Bullock-Webster fonds] \u2013 An album of color sketches, from the UBC Library Digital Collections, documenting social life and customs in Canadian fur trade posts in the 19th Century\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060716210108/http://www.whiteoak.org/learning/timeline.htm A Brief History of the Fur Trade]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/lakota_sioux_and_comanche_indians/11741638174/sizes/o/in/photostream/ Map of trading posts, forts, trails and Indian tribes] \n* [http://www.sojuzpushnina.ru/en/s/55/ History of the Fur Trade in Russia]\n* [http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/topics/shorthistory/furtrade.asp History of the Fur Trade in Wisconsin]\n* [http://www.furtrade.org Museum of the Fur Trade, Chadron, Nebraska USA]\n* [http://eh.net/encyclopedia/the-economic-history-of-the-fur-trade-1670-to-1870/ The Economic History of the Fur Trade: 1670 to 1870] (EH.Net Encyclopedia of Economic History)\n* [http://www.nps.gov/archive/crmo/hcs3a.htm Fur trade in the Snake River Valley, Idaho]\n* [http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/mb_history/32/furtraderevisited.shtml ''The Fur Trade Revisited \u2013 Manitoba Historical Society'']\n*\n\n{{Industries}}\n{{animal welfare}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fur Trade}}\n[[Category:Fur trade|*]]\n[[Category:History of the American West]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare]]\n[[Category:Fur|Trade]]\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added ink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fur_trade"}
{"title_page": "William Bourke Cockran", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish American Congressman}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = William Bourke Cockran\n|image        = File:William Bourke Cockran NY.jpg|\n|caption      =  Cockran at [[C. M. Bell]]'s studio\n|office       = Member of the<br />[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|term_start  = March 4, 1887 \n|term_end    = March 3, 1889\n|predecessor = [[Abraham Dowdney]]\n|successor   = [[Roswell P. Flower]]\n|constituency = {{ushr|NY|12|12th district}}\n|term_start1  = November 3, 1891\n|term_end1    = March 3, 1895\n|predecessor1 = [[Francis B. Spinola]]\n|successor1   = [[George B. McClellan Jr.]]\n|constituency1 = {{ushr|NY|10|10th district}} (1891\u201393)<br />{{ushr|NY|12|12th district}} (1893\u201395)\n|term_start2  = February 23, 1904\n|term_end2    = March 3, 1909 \n|predecessor2 = George B. McClellan Jr.\n|successor2   = [[Michael F. Conry]]\n|constituency2 = {{ushr|NY|12|12th district}}\n|term_start3   = March 4, 1921\n|term_end3     = March 1, 1923\n|constituency3 = {{ushr|NY|16|16th district}}\n|predecessor3  = [[Thomas Francis Smith|Thomas F. Smith]]\n|successor3    = [[John J. O'Connor (politician)|John J. O'Connor]]\n|birth_date   = February 28, 1854\n|birth_place  = [[County Sligo]], [[Ireland]]\n|death_date   = March 1, 1923 (aged 69)\n|death_place  = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|party        = [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]\n}}\n'''William Bourke Cockran''' (February 28, 1854 \u2013 March 1, 1923), commonly known as '''Bourke Cockran''', was an Irish-American politician. His name sometimes appears as '''Burke Cochran''' in contemporary newspaper reports. He served as a [[United States Representative]] from the [[East Side (Manhattan)|East Side of Manhattan]] for seven terms.\n\nCockran switched parties four times, but is best known as a Democrat. He was a leading orator of the late 19th and early 20th century, and an important influence on British statesman Winston Churchill, who noted that Cockran was a pacifist and capitalist, who vigorously fought against socialists, silver inflationists and advocates of high tariffs.<ref>Andrew Roberts, ''Churchill: Walking with Destiny'' (2018) p 35.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in Carrowkeel, [[County Sligo, Ireland]], he was educated in France and in his native country, and emigrated to the United States when seventeen years of age. He was a teacher in a private academy and principal of a public school in [[Westchester County, New York]]. He studied law, was admitted to the bar in 1876, and practiced in [[Mount Vernon, New York]]; two years later, he moved to New York City and continued the practice of law.  A devout [[Roman Catholic]],  he became deeply involved in support of Irish nationalism.<ref>Eoin Butler, \"The Irish orator who taught Winston Churchill how to win a crowd.'' [https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/the-irish-orator-who-taught-winston-churchill-how-to-win-a-crowd-1.2975643?mode=amp&mode=print&ot=example.AjaxPageLayout.ot  ''Irish Times] February 17, 2017, 15:5]</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:William Bourke Cockran.jpg|thumb|William Bourke Cockran photographed by C. M. Bell Studio]]\nBeginning in 1886, Cockran, a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], was a frequent candidate for the US House of Representatives and won several times; he served a number of non-consecutive terms. He was a delegate to the [[Democratic National Convention]]s in 1884, 1892, 1904, and 1920. At the 1920 convention, he delivered the nominating speech for [[Al Smith]].<ref>James McGurrin, ''Bourke Cockran: a free lance in American politics'' (Arno Press, 1972).</ref>\n\nCockran was a member of the commission to revise the judiciary article of the [[New York Constitution]] in 1890. Cockran publicly broke with his party in 1896, opposing the [[Free Silver]] platform of Democratic presidential candidate [[William Jennings Bryan]]. Cockran campaigned instead for Republican presidential candidate [[William McKinley]], which helped bring Gold Democrats over to McKinley's winning coalition.\n\nIn 1900, Cockran returned to the Democratic Party, supporting Bryan's second presidential campaign. Cockran returned to Congress in 1904 after he won a special election to fill the seat of [[George B. McClellan Jr.]], who had resigned to become [[mayor of New York City]].  He served his final years, 1921\u20131923, as a congressman, dying in Washington, D.C. He is buried in [[Gate of Heaven Cemetery]], [[Hawthorne, New York]].\n\nCockran, a friend of Britain's [[Churchill family]] and reputed one-time lover of [[Jennie Churchill]], introduced her 20-year-old son, [[Winston Churchill]], to American high society during Churchill's first trip to New York in 1895. Years later, Churchill credited Cockran as his first political mentor and the chief role model for his own success as an orator.  Churchill wrote in the 1930s that Cockran was, \"A pacifist, individualist, democrat, capitalist, and a 'Gold-bug'....He was equally opposed to socialists, inflationist, and Protectionists, and he resisted them on all occasions.\" Churchill never became a pacifist but he did adopt all the rest of Cockran's stances during his own political career, and carefully read and reread his speeches for oratorical advice.<ref>Andrew Roberts, ''Churchill: Walking with Destiny'' (2018) p 35.</ref>  Churchill quoted Cockran in his 1946 \"Iron Curtain speech\" recalling: \u201cwords which I learned 50 years ago from a great Irish-American orator, a friend of mine, Mr Bourke Cockran: \u2018There is enough for all. The earth is a generous mother. She will provide, in plentiful abundance, food for all her children, if they will but cultivate her soil in justice and in peace.\u2019\u201d [https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/the-irish-orator-who-taught-winston-churchill-how-to-win-a-crowd-1.2975643?mode=amp&mode=print&ot=example.AjaxPageLayout.ot]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1900\u201349)]]\n{{Portal bar|Biography|New York (state)}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gibson, Florence E. ''The attitudes of the New York Irish toward state and national affairs, 1848-1892'' (AMS Press, 1951).\n* Kennedy, Ambrose. ''American Orator: Bourke Cockran; His Life and Politics'' (1948). 225 pp. \n* McElroy, Robert, ed. ''In The Name Of Liberty: Selected Addresses Of William Bourke Cockran'' (1925)\n* McGurrin, James. ''Bourke Cockran: a free lance in American politics'' (Arno Press, 1972). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/23149554 Online review]\n* Stovall, Richard Lee. \"The rhetoric of Bourke Cockran: a contextual analysis\" (PhD dissertation, The Ohio State University, 1975).  [https://etd.ohiolink.edu/!etd.send_file?accession=osu1486993219479198&disposition=inline   Online]\n* {{cite book |title=Thom's Irish Who's Who |date=1923 |publisher=Alexander Thom and Son Ltd. |location=Dublin |pages=40-41 |chapter=[[s:Thom's Irish Who's Who/Cockran, William Bourke|Cockran, William Bourke]]}}\n\n{{CongBio|C000575}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Find a Grave|15079271}}\n*[http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.rbc/rbcmil.scrp5012301 Mrs. Bourke Cockran on woman suffrage] From a scrapbook in the Carrie Chapman Catt Collection in the Rare Book and Special Collection Division at the [[Library of Congress]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York|\n  district=12 |\n  before=[[Abraham Dowdney]] |\n  after= [[Roswell P. Flower]] |\n  years=1887\u20131889}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York|\n  district=10 |\n  before=[[Francis Spinola]] |\n  after= [[Daniel Sickles]] |\n  years=1891\u20131893}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York|\n  district=12 |\n  before=[[Joseph J. Little]] |\n  after= [[George B. McClellan Jr.]] |\n  years=1893\u20131895}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York|\n  district=12 |\n  before=[[George B. McClellan Jr.]] |\n  after= [[Michael Conry]] |\n  years=1904\u20131909}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York|\n  district=16 |\n  before=[[Thomas F. Smith]] |\n  after= [[John J. O'Connor (politician)|John J. O'Connor]] |\n  years=1921\u20131923}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cockran, William Bourke}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Burials at Gate of Heaven Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States (before 1923)|Cockran, W. Bourke]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)|Cockran, W. Bourke]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New York City|Cockran, W. Bourke]]\n[[Category:People from County Sligo]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Sligo]]\n[[Category:Laetare Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:American anti-socialists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish American Congressman}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = William Bourke Cockran\n|image        = File:William Bourke Cockran NY.jpg|\n|caption      =  Cockran at [[C. M. Bell]]'s studio\n|office       = Member of the<br />[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|term_start   = March 4, 1921\n|term_end     = March 1, 1923\n|constituency = {{ushr|NY|16|16th district}}\n|predecessor  = [[Thomas Francis Smith|Thomas F. Smith]]\n|successor    = [[John J. O'Connor (politician)|John J. O'Connor]]\n|term_start1  = February 23, 1904\n|term_end1    = March 3, 1909 \n|predecessor1 = [[George B. McClellan Jr.]]\n|successor1   = [[Michael F. Conry]]\n|constituency1 = {{ushr|NY|12|12th district}}\n|term_start2  = November 3, 1891\n|term_end2    = March 3, 1895\n|predecessor2 = [[Francis B. Spinola]]\n|successor2   = [[George B. McClellan Jr.]]\n|constituency2 = {{ushr|NY|10|10th district}} (1891\u201393)<br />{{ushr|NY|12|12th district}} (1893\u201395)\n|term_start3  = March 4, 1887 \n|term_end3    = March 3, 1889\n|predecessor3 = [[Abraham Dowdney]]\n|successor3   = [[Roswell P. Flower]]\n|constituency3 = {{ushr|NY|12|12th district}}\n|birth_date   = February 28, 1854\n|birth_place  = [[County Sligo]], [[Ireland]]\n|death_date   = March 1, 1923 (aged 69)\n|death_place  = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|party        = [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]\n}}\n'''William Bourke Cockran''' (February 28, 1854 \u2013 March 1, 1923), commonly known as '''Bourke Cockran''', was an Irish-American politician. His name sometimes appears as '''Burke Cochran''' in contemporary newspaper reports. He served as a [[United States Representative]] from New York City.  He switched parties four times, but is best known as a Democrat. He was a leading orator of the late 19th and early 20th century, and an important influence on British statesman Winston Churchill, who noted that Cockran was a pacifist and capitalist, who vigorously fought against socialists, silver inflationists and advocates of high tariffs.<ref>Andrew Roberts, ''Churchill: Walking with Destiny'' (2018) p 35.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in Carrowkeel, [[County Sligo, Ireland]], he was educated in France and in his native country, and emigrated to the United States when seventeen years of age. He was a teacher in a private academy and principal of a public school in [[Westchester County, New York]]. He studied law, was admitted to the bar in 1876, and practiced in [[Mount Vernon, New York]]; two years later, he moved to New York City and continued the practice of law.  A devout [[Roman Catholic]],  he became deeply involved in support of Irish nationalism.<ref>Eoin Butler, \"The Irish orator who taught Winston Churchill how to win a crowd.'' [https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/the-irish-orator-who-taught-winston-churchill-how-to-win-a-crowd-1.2975643?mode=amp&mode=print&ot=example.AjaxPageLayout.ot  ''Irish Times] February 17, 2017, 15:5]</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:William Bourke Cockran.jpg|thumb|William Bourke Cockran photographed by C. M. Bell Studio]]\nBeginning in 1886, Cockran, a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], was a frequent candidate for the US House of Representatives and won several times; he served a number of non-consecutive terms. He was a delegate to the [[Democratic National Convention]]s in 1884, 1892, 1904, and 1920. At the 1920 convention, he delivered the nominating speech for [[Al Smith]].<ref>James McGurrin, ''Bourke Cockran: a free lance in American politics'' (Arno Press, 1972).</ref>\n\nCockran was a member of the commission to revise the judiciary article of the [[New York Constitution]] in 1890. Cockran publicly broke with his party in 1896, opposing the [[Free Silver]] platform of Democratic presidential candidate [[William Jennings Bryan]]. Cockran campaigned instead for Republican presidential candidate [[William McKinley]], which helped bring Gold Democrats over to McKinley's winning coalition.\n\nIn 1900, Cockran returned to the Democratic Party, supporting Bryan's second presidential campaign. Cockran returned to Congress in 1904 after he won a special election to fill the seat of [[George B. McClellan Jr.]], who had resigned to become [[mayor of New York City]].  He served his final years, 1921\u20131923, as a congressman, dying in Washington, D.C. He is buried in [[Gate of Heaven Cemetery]], [[Hawthorne, New York]].\n\nCockran, a friend of Britain's [[Churchill family]] and reputed one-time lover of [[Jennie Churchill]], introduced her 20-year-old son, [[Winston Churchill]], to American high society during Churchill's first trip to New York in 1895. Years later, Churchill credited Cockran as his first political mentor and the chief role model for his own success as an orator.  Churchill wrote in the 1930s that Cockran was, \"A pacifist, individualist, democrat, capitalist, and a 'Gold-bug'....He was equally opposed to socialists, inflationist, and Protectionists, and he resisted them on all occasions.\" Churchill never became a pacifist but he did adopt all the rest of Cockran's stances during his own political career, and carefully read and reread his speeches for oratorical advice.<ref>Andrew Roberts, ''Churchill: Walking with Destiny'' (2018) p 35.</ref>  Churchill quoted Cockran in his 1946 \"Iron Curtain speech\" recalling: \u201cwords which I learned 50 years ago from a great Irish-American orator, a friend of mine, Mr Bourke Cockran: \u2018There is enough for all. The earth is a generous mother. She will provide, in plentiful abundance, food for all her children, if they will but cultivate her soil in justice and in peace.\u2019\u201d [https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/the-irish-orator-who-taught-winston-churchill-how-to-win-a-crowd-1.2975643?mode=amp&mode=print&ot=example.AjaxPageLayout.ot]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1900\u201349)]]\n{{Portal bar|Biography|New York (state)}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gibson, Florence E. ''The attitudes of the New York Irish toward state and national affairs, 1848-1892'' (AMS Press, 1951).\n* Kennedy, Ambrose. ''American Orator: Bourke Cockran; His Life and Politics'' (1948). 225 pp. \n* McElroy, Robert, ed. ''In The Name Of Liberty: Selected Addresses Of William Bourke Cockran'' (1925)\n* McGurrin, James. ''Bourke Cockran: a free lance in American politics'' (Arno Press, 1972). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/23149554 Online review]\n* Stovall, Richard Lee. \"The rhetoric of Bourke Cockran: a contextual analysis\" (PhD dissertation, The Ohio State University, 1975).  [https://etd.ohiolink.edu/!etd.send_file?accession=osu1486993219479198&disposition=inline   Online]\n* {{cite book 